<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  PMD ruleset for Nextcloud Deck macOS
  https://docs.pmd-code.org/latest/pmd_rules_swift.html

  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  NOTE: PMD static analysis (pmd check) is DISABLED for this project │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  PMD's Swift grammar is derived from an older language specification and
  cannot parse several constructs used throughout this codebase:

    • Existential types            any Encodable, any Error
    • if/switch expressions        let x = if cond { a } else { b }
    • async/await function sigs    func foo() async throws -> T
    • Trailing closures in SwiftUI .toolbar { }, .sheet(isPresented:) { }

  Attempting to run `pmd check` produces dozens of ANTLR parse warnings
  and one confirmed NPE bug in the UnavailableFunction rule (null function
  body on protocol/abstract declarations). The violations reported are
  therefore unreliable and cannot be acted on safely.

  CPD (copy-paste detection) IS still enabled and works correctly; it
  operates at the token level without requiring a full parse of every
  modern Swift construct. Run it via:

    pmd cpd --minimum-tokens 50 --dir NextcloudDeck --language swift

  This file is kept so the ruleset reference is preserved for when PMD's
  Swift grammar is updated to support Swift 5.9+. Track progress at:
    https://github.com/pmd/pmd/issues/new (search "Swift" in issues)

  Suppressing a CPD false-positive in source is not directly supported;
  use the --exclude-file-list CLI option if a file must be skipped.
  For pmd check violations (once re-enabled), use:
    // NOPMD - <reason>
-->
<ruleset name="Nextcloud Deck macOS Swift Ruleset"
         xmlns="http://pmd.sourceforge.net/ruleset/2.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://pmd.sourceforge.net/ruleset/2.0.0
                             https://pmd.sourceforge.net/ruleset_2_0_0.xsd">

    <description>
        PMD configuration for the Nextcloud Deck macOS Swift codebase.

        Static analysis rules are currently inactive because PMD's Swift grammar
        predates Swift 5.9 and cannot parse existential types, if/switch
        expressions, or async/await signatures — all of which are used throughout
        this project. Re-enable the rule references below once PMD ships an
        updated Swift grammar.

        CPD (copy-paste detection) is the active check; it is invoked directly
        via CLI flags in .pre-commit-config.yaml and pr-validation.yml rather
        than through this ruleset file.

        References:
          - https://docs.pmd-code.org/latest/pmd_rules_swift.html
          - https://deck.readthedocs.io/en/latest/API/
    </description>

    <!--
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    DISABLED RULES — re-enable when PMD Swift grammar supports Swift 5.9+
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    Best Practices
    ──────────────
    ProhibitedInterfaceBuilder (priority 2)
      This project is a pure SwiftUI app — no XIBs or Storyboards are used.
      Would catch any accidental @IBOutlet / @IBAction / @IBInspectable usage.

    <rule ref="category/swift/bestpractices.xml/ProhibitedInterfaceBuilder">
        <priority>2</priority>
    </rule>

    UnavailableFunction (priority 2)
      Functions marked @available(*, unavailable) (e.g. required init?(coder:)
      stubs) must call fatalError() rather than silently returning, so callers
      get an immediate, informative crash instead of undefined behaviour.
      Consistent with the existing `unavailable_function` SwiftLint rule.
      BLOCKED BY: NPE bug when functionBody() returns null on abstract decls.

    <rule ref="category/swift/bestpractices.xml/UnavailableFunction">
        <priority>2</priority>
    </rule>

    Error Prone
    ───────────
    ForceCast (priority 1)
      Force casts (as!) can crash at runtime. The codebase uses Codable —
      use conditional casts (as?) or typed decoding instead.

    <rule ref="category/swift/errorprone.xml/ForceCast">
        <priority>1</priority>
    </rule>

    ForceTry (priority 1)
      Force try (try!) suppresses structured error propagation and crashes on
      failure. All network and Keychain operations use async/await with explicit
      error handling; force try undermines that contract.

    <rule ref="category/swift/errorprone.xml/ForceTry">
        <priority>1</priority>
    </rule>

    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    END DISABLED RULES
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    -->

</ruleset>
